Reference-contexts: Practical lossless compression techniques usually impose some structure on the source sequence in the form of a model that can suitably represent the sequence. 2.1. Context models For image data, a particularly popular model that has been widely used is a context model <ref> [5] </ref>. Here, it is assumed that the distribution of the current symbol only depends on some limited context in which it occurs. <p> Context selection When using a context modeling technique for lossless compression, the question naturally arises: how does one select the contexts to be used for conditioning the probability estimation of the current symbol? Rissanen <ref> [5] </ref> has addressed these and other questions in a rigorous framework and given answers for a special class of finite-state models named tree models. He also presents an asymptotically optimal algorithm named CONTEXT for encoding a given data sequence by adaptively constructing a suitable context model.
