Reference-contexts: It has been our experience that lossless image compression implementations that employ a raster scan, usually outperform those that scan the image along a Hilbert space filling curve. One could possibly explain this discrepancy by the fact that the context based predictive techniques usually employed for lossless image compression <ref> [8] </ref>, are inherently designed with respect to a raster scan and are difficult to extend in a natural and consistent manner to work in conjunction with a Hilbert scan. <p> Associated with each context C is a probability distribution p (xjC) that is used to encode pixel X j when its context is C. This pdf can be estimated by maintaining counts of symbol occurrences within each context (as in CALIC <ref> [8] </ref>) or by estimating the parameters of an assumed pdf (as in JPEG-LS [1]). Once we have efficient estimates for the pdf within each context, coding can be done efficiently.
